Predicting Future Music Trends Using a Centuries' Worth of Data¶

By Kian Abdi

Introduction¶

Music is an art that can connect people from every single culture and edge of our vast world. With thousands of new songs being created/released daily, the ebb and flow of music appear to be endless. Throughout history, music has been communicated through many mediums and forms, but as more music comes into existence, more data about various music trends will be at our disposal. The ideal collection of this data occurs in the world of streaming, with services such as Spotify anchoring data for hundreds of thousands of songs.

To fully analyze these trends, we will be looking at a couple of datasets that contain song data for over 600 thousand songs, with the different sets being sorted by genre, artist, and year from 1921-2021. Furthermore, we will also be trying to see if it is possible to create a predictive model of a "combination" variable using the fundamentals of regression. This way we can use this project to predict future trends that may continue in music.

The datasets being used were accessed using the Spotify API, you can learn more about Spotify here: https://www.spotify.com/us/

Here is an article described some of the current changes that music is undergoing, see if you can find any similarities during our analysis! https://business-review.eu/lifestyle/music/trends-that-will-reshape-the-music-industry-216932

Furthermore, here is some more documentation for some of the libraries we will be using, feel free to refer to these resouces if you want to go further in-depth: https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/ https://seaborn.pydata.org/ https://matplotlib.org/stable/contents.html https://scikit-learn.org/stable/

Data Analysis¶

To begin our analysis, we will using following libraries: pandas, seaborn, and matplotlib. We will also import numpy for future use.

At a first look, some of the column names appear to be confusing, especially with their scaling. Luckily with the Spotify API: https://developer.spotify.com/documentation/web-api/reference/#category-tracks we are able to loosely understand how some of the columns in our dataframes are conceived. Let's take a look at a few of the descriptions from the API to see if we can find anything interesting.

  • Acousticness - A confidence measure from 0.0 to 1.0 of whether the track is acoustic. 1.0 represents high confidence the track is acoustic.
  • Danceability - describes how suitable a track is for dancing based on a combination of musical elements including tempo, rhythm stability, beat strength, and overall regularity. A value of 0.0 is least danceable and 1.0 is most danceable.
  • Energy - Energy is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy. For example, death metal has high energy, while a Bach prelude scores low on the scale. Perceptual features contributing to this attribute include dynamic range, perceived loudness, timbre, onset rate, and general entropy.
  • Loudness - The overall loudness of a track in decibels (dB). Loudness values are averaged across the entire track and are useful for comparing relative loudness of tracks. Loudness is the quality of a sound that is the primary psychological correlate of physical strength (amplitude). Values typical range between -60 and 0 db.
  • Popularity - The popularity of the track. The value will be between 0 and 100, with 100 being the most popular. The popularity is calculated by algorithm and is based, in the most part, on the total number of plays the track has had and how recent those plays are.
  • Speechiness - Speechiness detects the presence of spoken words in a track. The more exclusively speech-like the recording (e.g. talk show, audio book, poetry), the closer to 1.0 the attribute value. Values above 0.66 describe tracks that are probably made entirely of spoken words. Values between 0.33 and 0.66 describe tracks that may contain both music and speech, either in sections or layered, including such cases as rap music. Values below 0.33 most likely represent music and other non-speech-like tracks.
  • Valence - A measure from 0.0 to 1.0 describing the musical positiveness conveyed by a track. Tracks with high valence sound more positive (e.g. happy, cheerful, euphoric), while tracks with low valence sound more negative (e.g. sad, depressed, angry).

The majority of the above variables are derived from a single aspect of a track, but one that stands out in Danceability. Danceability is described as a "combination" of several musical elements. Although we can't exactly pinpoint the exact combination of factors, we will figure out a way to approach this later on in the tutorial. Danceability should be a very interesting variable to hone it, since its nature as a "combination" variables leads me to believe that the variable may be a very good indicator of future trends in music overall.

Upon further review of the columns in the dataframes above, it appears that some columns are linear combinations of each other. For example, the Spotify metric "Danceability" measures how danceable a track is from 0.0 to 1.0 scale, and to calculate this value the tempo of the song is taken into account. As a result, this means that tempo and danceability should be relatively related.

However, you might be asking, should we take into account both tempo and danceability since they are similar? The answer is not so simple, because in some situations with correlated data, weighting identical features can lead to specific features/variables of a model becoming unnecessarily biased. But in this case, there is no need to consider this, since tempo and danceability are still not identical, albeit similar.

Next, let us take a look at how the metrics from API have evolved with some scatterplots. To do this, we will utilize our dataframe that is sorted by year. Note we are also importing some new methods from sklearn, as we will be using linear regression with our plots.

Here is some documenation that documents how to make use of scipy's linear regression: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LinearRegression.html https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/linear-regression-in-python-from-scratch-with-scipy-statsmodels-sklearn-da8e373cc89b

# Importing linear regression for line of best fit on plot
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Set up correlation matrix to get initial idea of possible relations between columns
# A higher number in the heatmap indicates a higher correlation between variables!
plt.figure(figsize = (20, 10))
corrMatrix = data.corr()
sns.heatmap(corrMatrix, annot=True)
plt.show()

# creating list of lsits with year data for model training
X = [[i] for i in data_by_year['year']]

# fit linear regression for the data
linreg = LinearRegression()
linreg.fit(X, data_by_year['danceability'])

# make predictions with use of the training set
prediction = linreg.predict(X)

# Label, Setup, and Plot a scatterplot of how dancebility has evolved over time
plt.figure(figsize = (16, 10))
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=15, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Average Danceability (from 0.0 to 1.0)', fontsize=15, fontweight='bold')
plt.title('Average Danceability of Music Over Time', fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
sns.scatterplot(x=data_by_year['year'], y=data_by_year['danceability'], alpha=0.8, color=["navy"])
# plot line of best fit using model prediction from the linear regression
plt.plot(data_by_year['year'], prediction, color = "black", linewidth = 2)
plt.show()

As we can see, there are very obvious correlations and fluctuations between most of the variables we graphed across a one-hundred-year span. Now before we move on, let us take a look at some of these plots to see if we can make any surface-level assumptions of any trend or fluctuation. In the Danceability, Valence, Energy, and Tempo graphs, for example, I notice that there is a slight dip in the increasing trend during the mid-'40s. What happened in the 1940's you may ask? World War 2 is what happened, and although we can no way say this conclusively, it would make sense that the overall liveliness of music decreased during such a difficult time. Furthermore, since Valence, Energy, and Tempo experienced a drop during wartime as Danceability did, we should keep in mind that these Valence, Energy, and Tempo are potentially factored into Spotify's Danceability calculation. Another example that we can speculate on is the Speechiness graph, as the slight increase in speeches over the past couple of decades may be attributed to the prevalence of rap music in the realm of pop culture.

In Addition, from our heatmap we can see that the most heavily correlating variable to Danceability is Valence, so let us keep this in mind when trying to break down Danceability further in a little bit.

As for our next step, let us take some time to find some further insights from our data, and see if we can figure out the factors that go into a combination variable like Danceability.

As we can see from the plots, there is not a clear cut linear correlation between danceability or any of the 3 variables. We can attribute this since Danceability is a combination variable, in which we don't know the weights of its respective factors. Even though this step may appear to not be very useful, it, tells us something very important in data science, and that is to try as many avenues to derive a meaningful conclusion.

Let us see if we can dig deeper into danceability using our genre-specific dataframe.

Even if there was a direct correlation, the weights of other unknown factor elements would likely incur an unpredictable nature for danceability when it comes to viewing graphs.

Before we get to modeling, let us see if we can derive any further insights in regards to danceability using the other columns at our disposal, such as Popularity.

There still is no clear-cut correlation, but what happens if we consider splitting our data into time periods? At the beginning of this tutorial, we took note of the dip in Danceability during WW2, so it is possible that wrangling our data into time periods can give us the insight that we require. Let's continue by analyzing Popularity to see if we can translate any findings back to Danceability.

Here we see another very random scatterplot with no real trend when it comes to comparing popularity and danceability, meaning since the correlation between danceability and potential factors such as tempo was already random, we can reasonably assume that popularity is most likely not a factor in danceability. This can be verified by the fact that Danceability is derived from musical elements rather than consumer elements.

What did we gain during our Exploratory Data Analysis?¶

We now have a greater understanding of how trends have evolved on a decade-by-decade basis. Furthermore, we have ruled out non-musical elements as being factors of danceability, which betters allows us to realign focus on musical factors such as tempo and valence.

Finally, for our last step, we will train a regression model that can effectively predict the future value of danceability, giving a predictive insight into the future of music.

Machine Learning¶

## predict dancebiltiy

# create copy of data for regression and remove all non-numerical data
regression_data = data.copy()
del regression_data['artists']
del regression_data['id']
del regression_data['name']
del regression_data['period']
del regression_data['release_date']
regression_data

# fit regression with all variables besides danceability to see whether the model can train an effective regression
# using all variabels at our disposal
X = [[i] for i in regression_data['danceability']]
others =  regression_data.loc[:, regression_data.columns != 'danceability']
linreg.fit(X, others)

linreg.score(X, others)

linreg.predict(X)
b = linreg.intercept_
slope = linreg.coef_
slope_num = slope[0]
prediction = linreg.predict(X)
print("Change in danceability per year: " + str(slope_num))
print("R-Square: " + str(linreg.score(X, others)))

This is exactly what we wanted to find, the slope gives us the "predicted" value of change for danceabiltiy on a year to year basis. Since the past couple of years have been expontetial for the growth of dancability, our slope is a very high 0.83513486, which is lot consdiering the maximum danceabiltiy rating is 1.0. The only downside it that our R^2 value is a bit lower than preferred, so lets try retraining the model on specific columns/combinations

In [ ]:
X = [[i] for i in regression_data['danceability']]
others =  regression_data.loc[:, regression_data.columns != 'danceability']
linreg.fit(X, regression_data['valence'])

linreg.score(X, regression_data['valence'])

linreg.predict(X)
b = linreg.intercept_
slope = linreg.coef_
slope_num = slope[0]
prediction = linreg.predict(X)
print("Change in danceability per year: " + str(slope_num))
print("R-Square: " + str(linreg.score(X, regression_data['valence'])))

This is much better, as we have nearly increased our R-square value by 6 by opting to use Valence for our regression for Danceability. Notice the slope of 0.8351348570432082 is not much different from our combined regressions slope, meaning that this is an accurate predictive value to calculate danceability and further trends to come. Note that this approach will also work for any other variable, so we can modify the above code to predict the future values of any column variable such as tempo if we desire to do so. Finding the best variable for this was made easy by the heatmap we created earlier, as we already knew that the most heavily correlated variable to danceability was valence.

Documentation about basis linear regression: https://www.mathsisfun.com/data/least-squares-regression.html

Conclusion¶

There is so much music in the world that going through every trend and crevice is nearly impossible, and given the state of pop-culture, the path that music is on can change within a couple years of notice. However, despite this we were able to develop an accurate predictive model that could deliver a "forcast" into the potential future of music in the world.

With so many factors being in play, this is truly a dataset you can dig very deep into, as even though it may appear that two variales are similar, theres a good chance they are barely even related. This is why it is important to spend time during Exploratory Data Analysis, to not only answer questions you have but to derive more questions for further analysis.

As for the next steps in this project, I plan on developing a new model that can effectively provide a shortlist of song reccomendations based on a given track parameter. For an endeavor such as that, this tutorial is the perfect first step as being able to predict the future trends in music to an effective degree allows us to not only have a greater insignt, but a greater appreication to how incredible music really is. For example two polar opposite songs can both be hits, as it is just the nature of music. With this data comes a wall of opinions, which is part of the challenge of analyzing a cultural focal point such as music. Despite this, I hope that you were able to see that even in what appear to be useless visulizations, there is something to be derived, especially in the rich and in-depth dataset we utilizied. All in all, I hope that this tutorial was both intersting/helpful, and I am exited for you all to try come with your own music predictions and visualizations!
